activity that's conducted, primarily platinum mining.

500
00:31:02.208 --> 00:31:06.128
And then Vhembe, which is in the northern region of the country.

501
00:31:06.188 --> 00:31:08.308
This is a largely agricultural area.

502
00:31:08.908 --> 00:31:12.508
So even within the country, we have great diversity in terms of the

503
00:31:12.528 --> 00:31:14.988
environmental exposures that we expect to see.

504
00:31:16.028 --> 00:31:19.168
Similarly in Kenya, we recruit from three different sites,

505
00:31:19.648 --> 00:31:23.228
including Nairobi. Again, this is primarily industrial exposures.

506
00:31:23.658 --> 00:31:26.628
The Mount Kenya region, which is characterized by coffee

507
00:31:26.728 --> 00:31:27.688
plantations.

508
00:31:28.568 --> 00:31:32.108
And then the Eldoret region, which is sort of a mix of

509
00:31:32.288 --> 00:31:35.888
rural-urban, with agricultural activity

510
00:31:35.948 --> 00:31:37.968
occurring in this area.

511
00:31:40.668 --> 00:31:42.448
And so some of the work

512
00:31:44.348 --> 00:31:48.188
in the first phases of this consortium that this group has

513
00:31:48.248 --> 00:31:52.008
shown is one, just looking at the

514
00:31:53.008 --> 00:31:56.918
tumor mutational burden within samples that are collected

515
00:31:57.068 --> 00:31:58.707
from participants in this study.

516
00:31:59.728 --> 00:32:03.008
So in this early publication, using data from

517
00:32:03.168 --> 00:32:05.268
123 South African

518
00:32:06.188 --> 00:32:09.688
men, seven men from Brazil, and then 53

519
00:32:09.728 --> 00:32:10.988
individuals from

520
00:32:12.348 --> 00:32:14.848
Australia who are largely European ancestry,

521
00:32:15.868 --> 00:32:19.308
the group was able to characterize two million somatic

522
00:32:19.728 --> 00:32:22.928
mutations using whole genome sequencing within

523
00:32:23.748 --> 00:32:27.438
the prostate tumors. And was able to show using

524
00:32:27.468 --> 00:32:31.128
that data that there was a much greater tumor

525
00:32:31.208 --> 00:32:34.188
mutational burden among men of African ancestry.

526
00:32:35.408 --> 00:32:37.568
And then also using the

527
00:32:38.668 --> 00:32:41.688
mutational data, looking at the molecular

528
00:32:41.728 --> 00:32:44.308
taxonomy of the prostate cancers.

529
00:32:44.437 --> 00:32:45.108
And so

530
00:32:46.088 --> 00:32:49.548
using the global mutation subtypes framework,

531
00:32:51.448 --> 00:32:55.437
showing that there were global mutational subtypes that

532
00:32:55.448 --> 00:32:59.228
were specific to African ancestry populations.

533
00:33:00.128 --> 00:33:01.068
And so

534
00:33:02.848 --> 00:33:06.708
while we believe that genetics potentially contributes to some

535
00:33:06.748 --> 00:33:10.528
extent to tumor mutational burden, the

536
00:33:10.588 --> 00:33:13.588
external environmental characteristics leading to

537
00:33:15.328 --> 00:33:18.038
these factors has largely been understudied.

538
00:33:20.308 --> 00:33:24.148
This was another early study that was published using a

539
00:33:24.168 --> 00:33:25.368
subset of the

540
00:33:26.228 --> 00:33:29.748
tumor mutational data focusing on genes related

541
00:33:29.828 --> 00:33:32.748
to epigenetic machinery.

542
00:33:33.908 --> 00:33:37.808
And so again, looking across different ancestry populations, it

543
00:33:37.828 --> 00:33:40.768
was shown that among these

544
00:33:43.308 --> 00:33:47.188
genetic drivers, 63 of these were specific to

545
00:33:48.428 --> 00:33:52.418
African ancestry populations. Nine of these were

546
00:33:52.748 --> 00:33:56.528
ancestrally shared, so identified to be present in both African and

547
00:33:56.588 --> 00:34:00.308
European ancestry individuals. And only one of

548
00:34:00.368 --> 00:34:03.928
these driver mutations was observed to be European

549
00:34:04.028 --> 00:34:07.448
specific. So again, showing a much

550
00:34:07.568 --> 00:34:09.388
stronger burden of

551
00:34:10.649 --> 00:34:11.388
epigenetic

552
00:34:12.508 --> 00:34:15.908
associated mutations among African ancestry

553
00:34:15.919 --> 00:34:16.609
individuals.

554
00:34:18.379 --> 00:34:19.368
And then looking at

555
00:34:20.808 --> 00:34:24.308
the epigenome-wide signature within the tumor

556
00:34:24.388 --> 00:34:25.468
itself.

557
00:34:26.288 --> 00:34:29.448
The group has also shown that there is significant

558
00:34:29.488 --> 00:34:32.708
hypermethylation when you look at the epigenomic

559
00:34:33.129 --> 00:34:36.748
profile of prostate tissues collected

560
00:34:36.808 --> 00:34:40.669
from men of African ancestry relative to individuals

561
00:34:40.708 --> 00:34:44.467
of European ancestry. So this is sort of the genetic and

562
00:34:45.629 --> 00:34:49.548
molecular basis of some of the work that the consortium

563
00:34:49.629 --> 00:34:52.848
is conducting. And so

564
00:34:53.868 --> 00:34:56.748
one last element of this is also trying to understand

565
00:34:57.488 --> 00:35:00.978
geographic factors that are contributing to some of these

566
00:35:01.008 --> 00:35:04.968
differences. So for example, there's been work looking within

567
00:35:04.988 --> 00:35:08.968
South Africa itself to try to characterize some

568
00:35:09.028 --> 00:35:12.368
of the urban-rural differences that are being observed.

569
00:35:12.428 --> 00:35:16.328
So beyond just thinking about access to healthcare, what are some other

570
00:35:16.368 --> 00:35:19.208
factors that might be contributing to the differences?

571
00:35:20.668 --> 00:35:24.608
So as I mentioned, using the tumor mutational data,

572
00:35:25.388 --> 00:35:26.828
the group has identified

573
00:35:27.868 --> 00:35:28.288
genetic

574
00:35:30.108 --> 00:35:33.748
mutational subtypes. And so even just looking within South

575
00:35:33.808 --> 00:35:37.148
Africa, we see that there is a notable

576
00:35:37.188 --> 00:35:41.098
difference with respect to these molecular taxonomies that

577
00:35:41.128 --> 00:35:44.908
we observe among individuals living in the rural region versus

578
00:35:44.917 --> 00:35:46.148
those living in

579
00:35:47.348 --> 00:35:51.028
urban areas of the country. With individuals in

580
00:35:51.108 --> 00:35:54.748
the rural areas of the country having

581
00:35:56.008 --> 00:35:59.328
a molecular subtype that's characterized by copy number losses,

582
00:35:59.968 --> 00:36:03.848
which generally has been associated with poorer prognosis of

583
00:36:03.888 --> 00:36:05.928
prostate cancer within these individuals.

584
00:36:06.398 --> 00:36:09.828
So trying to understand within the country what are some of the factors that are

585
00:36:09.868 --> 00:36:12.078
contributing to this

586
00:36:12.688 --> 00:36:16.382
disparity.So the current phase of our

587
00:36:16.492 --> 00:36:20.082
work now is focused on overlaying environmental

588
00:36:20.232 --> 00:36:23.752
factors on the existing genetic and molecular data within the

589
00:36:23.772 --> 00:36:27.712
consortium. And so focusing to the best that we can on this

590
00:36:27.732 --> 00:36:31.372
exposomics framework, where we're looking broadly at

591
00:36:31.412 --> 00:36:34.902
different chemicals and features of the environment

592
00:36:35.372 --> 00:36:37.872
that may be contributing to

593
00:36:38.712 --> 00:36:42.402
developing prostate cancer, developing more aggressive

594
00:36:42.612 --> 00:36:46.352
prostate cancer, and then contributing to

595
00:36:46.392 --> 00:36:46.772
higher

596
00:36:47.752 --> 00:36:48.592
case fatality.

597
00:36:50.772 --> 00:36:51.432
And so

598
00:36:52.312 --> 00:36:54.051
similarly, when we think about

599
00:36:55.092 --> 00:36:55.612
what the

600
00:36:56.772 --> 00:36:59.892
public health and clinical implications of this work are,

601
00:37:00.872 --> 00:37:04.182
our hope is to be able to integrate environmental

602
00:37:04.312 --> 00:37:06.632
factors with genetic information,

603
00:37:08.832 --> 00:37:12.432
tumor information to be able to

604
00:37:14.332 --> 00:37:18.192
reduce disease onset, so decrease the risk of

605
00:37:18.472 --> 00:37:19.732
prostate cancer developing.

606
00:37:21.012 --> 00:37:24.532
Among individuals who already have signs of disease

607
00:37:24.612 --> 00:37:28.332
development, to be able to slow down progression or to switch to

608
00:37:29.612 --> 00:37:33.332
potentially a pathway that leads to less aggressive disease,

609
00:37:33.932 --> 00:37:37.832
and then to also be able to provide information to improve

610
00:37:37.912 --> 00:37:41.052
prognosis among individuals that develop prostate cancer.

611
00:37:43.112 --> 00:37:44.032
And so

612
00:37:45.152 --> 00:37:48.932
really, I think, our ultimate goal is to try to

613
00:37:48.972 --> 00:37:51.472
characterize the exposome within these individuals.

614
00:37:51.972 --> 00:37:55.432
And I will say, if we define the exposome as the

615
00:37:55.472 --> 00:37:58.192
totality of exposures across the life course,

616
00:37:59.132 --> 00:38:02.112
in practice, this is actually very difficult

617
00:38:03.072 --> 00:38:04.432
to do. And so,

618
00:38:05.372 --> 00:38:08.112
currently what we're trying to

619
00:38:09.072 --> 00:38:10.072
do within this

620
00:38:11.592 --> 00:38:15.272
research program is to at least focus on characterizing the

621
00:38:15.312 --> 00:38:16.552
physical and chemical

622
00:38:17.492 --> 00:38:21.052
environment of individuals around the time of their

623
00:38:21.152 --> 00:38:24.711
disease diagnosis. So using that as a starting point,

624
00:38:25.211 --> 00:38:28.992
and then hopefully in the future, having the ability to build

625
00:38:29.092 --> 00:38:29.272
out

626
00:38:30.972 --> 00:38:34.732
information on historical exposures or exposures to other features of the

627
00:38:34.752 --> 00:38:35.392
environment.

628
00:38:37.792 --> 00:38:41.552
And so our initial focus as a research group has been

629
00:38:41.652 --> 00:38:45.131
characterizing a broad spectrum of chemicals that we consider to be

630
00:38:45.192 --> 00:38:47.072
endocrine-disrupting chemicals.

631
00:38:47.932 --> 00:38:51.362
For those that may not be familiar with this class of chemicals,

632
00:38:52.272 --> 00:38:56.172
these are exogenous chemicals that are known to alter

633
00:38:56.252 --> 00:38:57.232
hormone activity.

634
00:38:58.312 --> 00:39:01.652
In the context of prostate cancer, this is important when we think about

635
00:39:01.732 --> 00:39:03.152
androgens and estrogens,

636
00:39:04.412 --> 00:39:08.252
and particularly when exposure to these chemicals occurs

637
00:39:08.262 --> 00:39:11.952
during critical windows of either prostate development or adult

638
00:39:11.992 --> 00:39:12.962
homeostasis.

639
00:39:14.232 --> 00:39:16.472
So it can contribute to prostate cancer

640
00:39:17.332 --> 00:39:20.712
development by disrupting cellular, epigenetic, or

641
00:39:20.812 --> 00:39:24.732
microenvironmental processes that can increase susceptibility

642
00:39:24.812 --> 00:39:28.332
to cancer developing, the progression of cancer, the

643
00:39:28.372 --> 00:39:29.512
recurrence of cancer.

644
00:39:30.692 --> 00:39:32.672
So, it's been shown that

645
00:39:32.752 --> 00:39:36.452
endocrine-disrupting chemicals can either mimic,

646
00:39:36.612 --> 00:39:39.992
block, or alter the synthesis release, transport,

647
00:39:40.132 --> 00:39:43.472
metabolism, binding, or elimination of

648
00:39:44.952 --> 00:39:48.712
endogenous hormones that regulate prostate growth and differentiation.

649
00:39:50.052 --> 00:39:53.872
And there have been many chemicals that are ubiquitous in the environment that have

650
00:39:53.892 --> 00:39:57.772
been well-characterized as endocrine-disrupting chemicals.

651
00:39:58.312 --> 00:40:02.152
So some of these that you may be familiar with are compounds

652
00:40:02.212 --> 00:40:05.792
like bisphenol A, various phthalates that are used as

653
00:40:05.812 --> 00:40:06.812
plasticizers,

654
00:40:08.052 --> 00:40:11.192
legacy exposures like PCBs, various

655
00:40:11.272 --> 00:40:15.152
pesticides, and then an emerging class of chemicals that we're

656
00:40:15.192 --> 00:40:18.672
becoming increasingly concerned with, known as

657
00:40:18.792 --> 00:40:22.752
PFAS, as well as a subset of metals that are known to have endocrine-disrupting

658
00:40:23.392 --> 00:40:24.252
activity as well.

659
00:40:25.812 --> 00:40:29.192
And so there have been a number of mechanisms related to

660
00:40:29.232 --> 00:40:32.911
exposure to endocrine-disrupting chemicals that are

661
00:40:32.952 --> 00:40:35.932
associated with potentially the development of prostate

662
00:40:36.031 --> 00:40:37.102
cancer,

663
00:40:37.962 --> 00:40:41.372
including alterations to cell proliferation or

664
00:40:41.992 --> 00:40:45.302
apoptosis, contributing to inflammation,

665
00:40:46.052 --> 00:40:48.272
changes in prostate size or histology,

666
00:40:49.172 --> 00:40:52.792
altering hormone receptor expression or signaling,

667
00:40:52.812 --> 00:40:54.522
contributing to

668
00:40:56.112 --> 00:41:00.032
somatic mutations or epigenetic changes, and

669
00:41:00.072 --> 00:41:02.752
then modulation of the tumor microenvironment.

670
00:41:03.732 --> 00:41:05.312
And so, while

671
00:41:06.552 --> 00:41:09.752
I think there's very strong experimental data to

672
00:41:09.812 --> 00:41:13.552
support the association of these chemical exposures

673
00:41:13.612 --> 00:41:17.552
with prostate cancer in general, I would say that the

674
00:41:17.572 --> 00:41:20.512
epidemiologic evidence is very mixed.

675
00:41:21.092 --> 00:41:24.152
So it's been difficult for many reasons

676
00:41:25.152 --> 00:41:29.012
to really characterize the role of these chemicals

677
00:41:29.052 --> 00:41:31.932
within the context of prostate cancer.

678
00:41:32.872 --> 00:41:33.292
And so,

679
00:41:34.192 --> 00:41:38.032
I think some of the challenges that this consortium is primarily

680
00:41:38.112 --> 00:41:39.372
focused on

681
00:41:40.272 --> 00:41:40.942
contributing,

682
00:41:42.092 --> 00:41:45.942
I think, novel data to is thinking about the role

683
00:41:46.292 --> 00:41:50.172
of genetic susceptibility in the context of exposure to

684
00:41:50.212 --> 00:41:54.012
these chemicals. So when we look at exposure within an

685
00:41:54.092 --> 00:41:57.172
average population, we may be missing important

686
00:41:57.592 --> 00:42:01.052
environmental signals that when we're not looking

687
00:42:01.112 --> 00:42:04.592
among genetically susceptible individuals,

688
00:42:05.052 --> 00:42:08.682
we may not be able to capture well or characterize well.

689
00:42:10.392 --> 00:42:13.842
The other consideration is thinking about disease aggressiveness.

690
00:42:13.972 --> 00:42:17.062
And so, similar to other risk factors like obesity,

691
00:42:17.532 --> 00:42:21.352
endocrine-disrupting chemicals may be specifically contributing to more

692
00:42:21.372 --> 00:42:24.352
aggressive prostate cancers. And so,

693
00:42:25.052 --> 00:42:27.512
focusing our investigations among

694
00:42:28.732 --> 00:42:31.212
that subpopulation of individuals.

695
00:42:31.852 --> 00:42:33.352
And then finally, thinking about

696
00:42:34.692 --> 00:42:38.532
what pathways or molecular data would

697
00:42:38.592 --> 00:42:42.332
help strengthen the evidence within human studies

698
00:42:42.892 --> 00:42:46.412
that endocrine-disrupting chemicals are contributing

699
00:42:46.492 --> 00:42:47.032
to

700
00:42:47.912 --> 00:42:50.794
cancer initiation.So from

701
00:42:51.684 --> 00:42:55.484
an environmental epidemiologic perspective, I

702
00:42:55.544 --> 00:42:58.764
also think that this is a particularly challenging

703
00:42:59.524 --> 00:43:03.364
topic of study because we know that timing of exposure

704
00:43:03.424 --> 00:43:05.944
may be critical to many of these hypotheses.

705
00:43:06.484 --> 00:43:10.264
And so, for example, if exposure occurs during sensitive

706
00:43:10.324 --> 00:43:12.584
periods like the prenatal period,

707
00:43:13.704 --> 00:43:17.644
the perinatal period, or during puberty, individuals may

708
00:43:17.704 --> 00:43:21.304
be particularly susceptible to the effects of those chemical

709
00:43:21.364 --> 00:43:24.504
exposures during those particular life periods.

710
00:43:24.964 --> 00:43:28.764
And so we need to be, I think, very deliberate in terms of when

711
00:43:28.844 --> 00:43:32.404
we're measuring exposure and how we're relating it to

712
00:43:32.724 --> 00:43:33.664
disease outcome.

713
00:43:34.964 --> 00:43:38.414
The other consideration is that endocrine-disrupting

714
00:43:38.484 --> 00:43:42.464
chemicals are known to have effects even at low doses of

715
00:43:42.524 --> 00:43:45.804
exposure. And these associations may not

716
00:43:45.844 --> 00:43:49.704
necessarily be monotonic, which means that if we have

717
00:43:49.714 --> 00:43:53.614
data on high-level exposures, that may not necessarily

718
00:43:53.624 --> 00:43:57.284
inform what the association will be in the low dose

719
00:43:57.384 --> 00:44:01.144
range and vice versa. And so ensuring that we have

720
00:44:01.504 --> 00:44:04.424
more comprehensive data for exposures

721
00:44:04.484 --> 00:44:05.504
within

722
00:44:06.864 --> 00:44:09.344
the complete dose response range.

723
00:44:10.664 --> 00:44:13.964
The other consideration is thinking about environmental mixtures.

724
00:44:14.424 --> 00:44:18.084
So much of the epidemiologic literature has focused on single

725
00:44:18.164 --> 00:44:21.914
chemicals in isolation, looking at the effects of an individual metal

726
00:44:22.504 --> 00:44:22.944
or

727
00:44:24.244 --> 00:44:27.894
BPA individually. But we know that individuals are not

728
00:44:27.924 --> 00:44:31.744
exposed in the real world to a single environmental exposure at a

729
00:44:31.844 --> 00:44:35.704
time. And so thinking about this within a framework where we can

730
00:44:35.904 --> 00:44:38.624
study the mixture as a whole or

731
00:44:39.624 --> 00:44:43.534
a more representative representation of somebody's environmental

732
00:44:43.604 --> 00:44:46.444
exposures more comprehensively.

733
00:44:46.924 --> 00:44:50.744
Other characteristics that we need to consider is that many of these chemicals

734
00:44:50.784 --> 00:44:54.424
have very short half-lives. So unless somebody has chronic

735
00:44:54.484 --> 00:44:58.224
exposure to these environmental exposures, using

736
00:44:58.264 --> 00:44:59.144
either a single

737
00:44:59.944 --> 00:45:03.704
urine or blood sample at a single moment in time may not

738
00:45:03.764 --> 00:45:07.324
be a good characterization of somebody's exposure to that

739
00:45:07.364 --> 00:45:11.324
particular chemical. And so thinking about what is the context

740
00:45:11.334 --> 00:45:14.024
that somebody is being exposed to and

741
00:45:16.224 --> 00:45:19.404
how well are we capturing it with the exposures that we're measuring.

742
00:45:20.104 --> 00:45:22.484
And then, I think with much of the

743
00:45:23.644 --> 00:45:26.954
work that's being done in cancer epidemiology, taking latency into

744
00:45:27.024 --> 00:45:28.384
consideration. And so,

745
00:45:29.184 --> 00:45:32.684
what is the relevant exposure window for many of these

746
00:45:33.764 --> 00:45:37.584
environmental factors contributing to cancer development?

747
00:45:39.284 --> 00:45:39.504
So

748
00:45:40.484 --> 00:45:44.004
just for the sake of time, I'll move on to the specific environmental assays that

749
00:45:44.044 --> 00:45:46.904
we've prioritized within this consortium.

750
00:45:47.604 --> 00:45:51.464
We have collected toenail clippings from all

751
00:45:51.504 --> 00:45:55.124
participants in the study, and we use these toenail clippings as a measure

752
00:45:55.284 --> 00:45:55.764
of

753
00:45:56.824 --> 00:46:00.744
longer-term exposure to a wide panel of metals.

754
00:46:01.524 --> 00:46:04.544
We also collect urine samples and plasma

755
00:46:04.624 --> 00:46:06.084
samples that

756
00:46:06.984 --> 00:46:10.934
we've prioritized looking at DDT and DDE exposures within

757
00:46:10.944 --> 00:46:14.674
the population. So while use of this chemical was

758
00:46:14.704 --> 00:46:18.244
banned in the United States in 1972, it's still

759
00:46:18.344 --> 00:46:21.964
used in certain regions of Africa for malaria control.

760
00:46:22.084 --> 00:46:24.504
So we know that there's ongoing exposure to

761
00:46:25.704 --> 00:46:28.264
this particular compound. We're also

762
00:46:29.164 --> 00:46:31.344
interested in looking at the effects of pyrethroids.

763
00:46:31.404 --> 00:46:34.584
These are largely used as insecticides as well as

764
00:46:35.404 --> 00:46:36.864
some organic pesticides.

