944
00:57:17.622 --> 00:57:21.562
As I mentioned, I'm an immunologist, so the main question in my lab is how

945
00:57:21.602 --> 00:57:23.822
does the immune system operate in solid tumors?

946
00:57:25.502 --> 00:57:29.422
You probably all know that we have these really potent killers in our body

947
00:57:29.462 --> 00:57:33.242
called T cells that can be very potent in killing cancer cells.

948
00:57:34.102 --> 00:57:37.122
But in solid tumors, the situation is a lot more complex.

949
00:57:37.982 --> 00:57:41.402
So this is a human colorectal cancer specimen, and you can

950
00:57:41.482 --> 00:57:45.452
see that the cancer cells are here, epithelial cells that are very tightly

951
00:57:45.502 --> 00:57:48.522
packed and intermingled with the tumor stroma.

952
00:57:50.162 --> 00:57:53.942
So for the immune cells to even find the cancer cells, they need to

953
00:57:54.042 --> 00:57:56.481
navigate these really complex

954
00:57:57.362 --> 00:58:01.022
environments. They need to talk to a lot of different cells and really

955
00:58:01.122 --> 00:58:02.682
cannot function in isolation.

956
00:58:03.542 --> 00:58:07.362
We think about the tumor stroma both as kind of the highways for the immune

957
00:58:07.422 --> 00:58:11.312
cells. This is where the vessels are, but this is also where the fibroblasts are,

958
00:58:11.362 --> 00:58:15.122
and this is also physical barriers that the immune cells need to overcome in order

959
00:58:15.162 --> 00:58:17.402
to even get to the cancer cells they target.

960
00:58:19.582 --> 00:58:23.522
So to understand how that actually works in human patients, we decided

961
00:58:23.602 --> 00:58:25.662
to take a look at a success story.

962
00:58:26.982 --> 00:58:29.502
And colon cancer is a really interesting

963
00:58:30.602 --> 00:58:32.022
example here in this regard.

964
00:58:32.882 --> 00:58:33.662
You might be familiar

965
00:58:34.642 --> 00:58:38.322
with Andreas Zerbst's really inspiring work in rectal

966
00:58:38.382 --> 00:58:42.262
